nodes.Label: Matter is always in one of three different physical states.
In a liquid, particles break bonds and form new bonds continuously.
When a solid is heated to its melting point it will melt.
The 3 physical states
The 3 physical states are solid, liquid and gas.
When a liquid is heated to its boiling point it will evaporate.
Gases
In gases, particles don't form bonds with each other.
Liquids
All particles vibrate all the time.
Particles can change the intensity of their vibration.
Hotter particles are particles that vibrate stronger.
The hotter a particle is the more it will push neighboring particles apart.
Solids expand when heated.
Liquids slightly expand when heated.
Gases expand when heated.
The melting point is the temperature at which a solid turns into a liquid or a liquid into a solid.
The boiling point is the temperature at which a liquid turns into a gas or a gas into a liquid.
During melting, particles vibrate with enough intensity to break bonds to neighboring particles and form new bonds with other particles.
During evaporation, particles in a liquid vibrate with enough intensity to break the bonds to each other completely.
Melting is the process of turning a solid into a liquid.
Evaporation is the process of turning a liquid into a gas.
Condensation is the process of turning a gas into a liquid.
Freezing is the process of turning a liquid into a solid.
Sublimation is the process of turning a liquid into a gas or vice versa.
Melting and freezing occur at the melting point.
Evaporation and condensation occur at the boiling point.
